<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-639-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 639 020.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Sept 11 1989 n265 p42(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CO-LANs catching on for cost-effective connectivity that leavesroom to grow. (Bell Atlantic Corp.; includes related article onhow CO-LAN works)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rockwell, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bell Atlantic's CO-LAN local area network provides voice and dataconnections with existing phone lines.andP;  About 100 customers use25,000 CO-LAN ports, paying a monthly fee of $25 per port.andP;  Thedata-voice multiplexors used in the LAN cost $170 to $200 each.andO;Besides being a faster way of transmitting data than using dial-upmodems, CO-LAN can also be used to supplement a company's otherLANs.andP;  Some users have noticed drawbacks.andP;  A centrex service isnecessary for CO-LAN implementation.andP;  Large file-servingoperations are not recommended, nor are applications that use alot of bandwidth.andP;  Some analysts claim the cost of buying andmaintaining a premises LAN is about the same as that of CO-LAN.andO;The majority of CO-LAN customers are large to mid-sizeenvironments like universities, city government or hospitals.andO;CO-LAN use by West Chester University and the city of Alexandria,VA is profiled.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Bell Atlantic Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    BEL.andO;Product:   CO-LAN (Local area network) (usage).andO;Topic:     Colleges and UniversitiesLocal Area NetworksGovernment AgencyData CommunicationsVoice CommunicationsCase Study.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>